@node FUTURE "Apache in the future"

I have some ideas for the next version(s) of Apache:

  · Finish the SysEx dump window
  · Implement a MIDI sample up/downloader
  · Use the camd.library instead of home made routines

If you have any ideas tell @{" me " link AUTH} about them!
@endnode

@node PIANO "The Piano Window"

This window enables you to easily check out how your patches sound
even if you don't have a stand-alone keyboard.

You can play with the mouse or with the keyboard. On a normal computer
keyboard there are not enough keys to fully cover more than 3 octaves 
so you can select "octave mode" with the cursor keys: Cursor up increases
the octave and cursor down goes one octave down.

You have some control over the MIDI data generated by this piano by
using the gadgets at the right of the window:

The gadget at the top right corner is the MIDI channel to broadcast
notes on.

The slider below determines the velocity of the MIDI notes send out.
@endnode

@node INTRO "Intro"

@{u}What is Apache?@{uu}
Apache is a modular patch editor for MIDI devices. With Apache itself 
you cannot make any patches for your synth - for that you'll need some 
Apache-PlugIn modules.

Plug-In modules available:

  · Roland JV-1080 / XP-50  (on Aminet: mus/midi/rolandjv1080.lha)
  · Roland JV-80            (on Aminet: mus/midi/rolandjv80.lha)

The Apache program controls the MIDI port and gives you features like
MIDI echo and a MIDI-piano window and acts like a home for the PlugIn
modules.
  
@endnode

@node REQ "Requirements"

@{u}Requirements@{uu}
You'll need KickStart 2.0 or better and @{" MUI " link MUI} v3.3 installed.
  
At least 1MB RAM, more is recommended.
  
A fast Amiga - some of the Apache PlugIns have quite comprehensive user 
interfaces and needs some power to work smoothly. I think it's okay on 
an A4000/030 and nice on an A4000/040. If you got something faster, you 
should be flying ;)

And you will of course need some MIDI equipment if you want to hear the
sounds you create :)
@endnode

@node MUI "MUI"

@{u}MUI - Magic User Interface@{uu}
Apache uses MUI to create the graphical user interface (GUI).
Use the MUI-prefs program to set things up the way you want it.
You start this program by selecting "MUI" in the settings menu.
  
MUI is available on Aminet and probably many other places. Get the
package called something like @{b}mui33usr.lha@{ub}. 
@endnode

